module sunholo/motoko_ext_eval/prompts

import pkg/sunholo/motoko_ext_abi/types (PromptPatch)

export func prompt_patch() -> PromptPatch {
  {
    prepend: [],
    append: [
      "Eval tool: use `eval` for persistent Python, JavaScript, AILANG, or Lean cells. Use py/js for scripts, data inspection, plotting, and quick calculations. Use `ail` for typed pure functions with SMT-checkable `requires`/`ensures` contracts. Use `lean` for arbitrary theorem proving, inductive proofs, and mathematical propositions. Cells keep state for this session. Each cell is `{language:\"py\"|\"js\"|\"ail\"|\"lean\", code, title?, timeout?, reset?}`. Py/js expose `display(value)`, workdir-confined `tool.*` helpers, and `agent(...)`. Eval kernels are native effect hatches: workdir file access is confined, external network is disabled by default, and in-cell tools are a fixed local allowlist.",
      "Eval with `language:\"ail\"` is a persistent, source-backed AILANG scratchpad (NOT a mutable REPL): accepted top-level declarations and imports accumulate as source for the session, and a later cell may use earlier declarations. Choose AILANG over py/js when you want type-checked, optionally machine-verified logic (pure functions with `requires`/`ensures` contracts proved by Z3); choose py/js for quick scripting, data wrangling, or plotting. Every `ail` candidate is gated by `ailang check`; a candidate that fails check (or required verification) is NOT committed and never mutates prior accepted state. Duplicate top-level names are rejected — use `reset:true` to start over. Cell fields: `{language:\"ail\", code, verify?:\"auto\"|\"required\"|\"off\", run?, entry?, caps?}`. You do NOT know AILANG syntax from memory: the FIRST `ail` cell's result carries a one-time AILANG teaching guide (in `metadata.ailang.teachPrompt`, also shown on the eval card) — read it, and consult `ailang prompt`, before relying on guessed syntax.",
      "AILANG proof caveat: a result is proven ONLY when `metadata.ailang.verify` is exactly `verified`. The statuses `unknown`, `timeout`, `skipped` (including when Z3 is unavailable), and `failed` are NOT proofs — never tell the user a value or contract is 'verified'/'proven' unless the verifier actually proved it. Report `skipped`/`unknown`/`timeout` honestly.",
      "Eval with `language:\"lean\"` is a persistent Lean 4 proof scratchpad. Accepted declarations persist through the Lean REPL env; a failed elaboration or failed required proof is NOT committed. Cell fields: `{language:\"lean\", code, prove?:\"auto\"|\"required\"|\"off\", mathlib?}`. Use named `theorem`/`lemma` declarations when you want a full machine-checkable verdict; anonymous `example`s cannot be axiom-audited. Before writing Lean cells, read the one-time Lean 4 guide shown in the first Lean cell result; do not guess Lean 3 syntax.",
      "Lean proof caveat: a Lean result is proven ONLY when `metadata.lean.proof` is exactly `verified`. The statuses `sorry`, `axiom_tainted`, `skipped`, `failed`, and `error` are NOT proofs. `sorry`/`admit`, custom axioms, and `native_decide` trust axioms must be reported honestly. `#eval` can run real IO/process code, so Lean cells are treated at least as strictly as py/js for execution policy."
    ]
  }
}
